Guide to the David Trinidad Papers

This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2016-06-08T10:51-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: Born in California in 1953, David Trinidad is a poet and teacher. He studied under Ann Stanford, Allen Ginsberg and Joan Larkin, and early in his career, he was the editor and publisher of Sherwood Press which published titles by such poets as: Dennis Cooper, Amy Gerstler, Tim Dlugos, and Alice Notley. Trinidad's own books of poems include: Pavane (1981); Monday, Monday (1985); Living Doll (1986); November (1987); Three Stories (1988); A Taste of Honey, with Bob Flanagan (1990); Answer Song (1994); Plasticville, (2000). He has been associated with the Beyond Baroque Literary/Arts Center in Venice, California and has an M.F.A. in Poetry from Brooklyn College. Currently Director of the Graduate Poetry Program at Columbia College in Chicago, he was previously on the Core Faculty of the M.F.A. Program at the New School in Manhattan. He has also taught at Princeton, Rutgers, and Antioch (Los Angeles).

p.value: Open to researchers. Appointments are necessary for the use of manuscript and archival materials.

                    <item>LIVING DOLL. Los Angeles: Illuminati, 1986.</item>
                    <item>NOVEMBER. New York: Hanuman Books, 1987.</item>
                    <item>PAVANE (revised edition). Los Angeles: Illuminati, 1988.</item>
                    <item>THREE STORIES. New York: Hanuman Books, 1988.</item>
                    <item>A TASTE OF HONEY (with Bob Flanagan). Los Angeles: Cold Calm Press, 1990.</item>
                    <item>HAND OVER HEART: POEMS 1981-1988. New York: Amethyst Press, 1991.</item>
                    <item>ANSWER SONG. New York: High Risk Books, 1994.</item>
                    <item>POWERLESS: SELECTED POEMS 1973-1990 by Tim Dlugos (editor). New York: High Risk Books, 1996.</item>
                    <item>ESSAY WITH MOVEABLE PARTS. Normal: Thorngate Road, 1998.</item>
